<font color="#FF0000">TO EDWARD HUMMING EAGLE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 14 11:57:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward Humming Eagle,<br><br>
In one of your poems from your &quot;Scars and Stripes&quot; collection you mentioned how Vietnam Veterans were thrown away.<br><br>
We can reflect upon those days with some sadness, of course. <br>
I choose to attempt to make something *positive* from the &quot;homecoming&quot; experience. For the first time in my life I experienced what it was like to be shunned - not as much personally - but rather I felt saddened by the stereotypes that all Vietnam Vets fell prey to.  <br><br>
I don't dare compare what I endured to the plight of minorities. But, I felt hurt, all the same. There will always be &quot;Scars and Stripes&quot;.<br><br>
May I be so bold as to say that the anger you feel may be better understood if you put it in the context of what your tribal ancestors experienced? I don't pretend to know much about Native American culture, yet I feel safe in presuming that there has been much anger towards European &quot;pioneers&quot;. Anger probably still remains in some quarters.<br><br>
You have mentioned that your father is a Veterinarian. You and your brother served our country in Vietnam. Somewhere along the way your family had to be able to see past the anger in order to be successful and to be part of a different (not necessarily better) system. <br><br>
One only has to read the spiritual posts you have written in this thread to see that you and your family continue to enjoy the &quot;best of both worlds&quot;. Could angry people do this? Does anger alleviate sadness? We can vent our anger all we like, but the sadness always drifts back to the surface. <br><br>
There is a better way.<br><br>
In the FORUM section of this Website one of the participants, Mr Earl Martin, had this to say in his biography: <br><br>
&quot;I believe the Vietnam vet serves, in a profound<br>
way, as the most poignant conscience of American society. Given all the shit and sacred trauma the Vet has experienced he/she has become (collectively and personally) a sort of a &quot;seer&quot; in American society. If there is any hope of salvation for our society, I believe the vet will have an important role in defining and shaping that vision.&quot;<br><br>
This is the challenge that all who served in Vietnam should proudly and willingly accept. We can never forget the past. I saw the best and the worst in men during my time in Vietnam. However, I would not trade the experience for anything in the world - the reason being, that I hope to use that experience to be part of what the above statement by Earl Martin suggests is attainable.<br><br>
The only things that can confuse or sidetrack us is allowing ourselves to be tripped up by anger and bitterness.<br><br>
I would very much like to hear more about your family heritage, Humming Eagle, for I believe that many answers can be found therein.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net.  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


